WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.440
Hi, my name is Rika Gorn, and thank you for coming to my talk, From Zero to Hero, Best

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:19.160
Practices for Setting Up RStudio in the Cloud.

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:23.200
So last year, I was given the keys to an incredible treasure.

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:26.160
And when I say keys, I mean literally keys.

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:30.400
I was handed three product keys so that my data science team at Spring Health, where

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:38.080
I work, could start using RStudio Server Pro, RStudio Connect, and RStudio Package Manager.

00:00:38.080 --> 00:00:40.880
Now my name is Rika Gorn, and I'm a data scientist.

00:00:40.880 --> 00:00:42.799
I'm not an engineer.

00:00:42.799 --> 00:00:46.360
I work at an incredible organization called Spring Health.

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:50.680
We're a mental health care tech startup that provides a comprehensive mental health care

00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:54.340
solution to employers all over the world.

00:00:54.340 --> 00:00:58.099
Over the last year, we've been growing and scaling a ton.

00:00:58.099 --> 00:01:00.619
And side note, we are hiring.

00:01:00.619 --> 00:01:06.940
And RStudio Team would be a huge win for a very quickly growing data science team.

00:01:06.940 --> 00:01:09.419
So what did this mean for me and my team?

00:01:09.419 --> 00:01:14.940
Well, RStudio Server Pro would allow us to run R in a secure, remote environment, and

00:01:14.940 --> 00:01:20.339
we wouldn't have to rely on our local computer for computationally expensive jobs.

00:01:20.339 --> 00:01:25.059
RStudio Connect would allow us to publish all of our data products, including Shiny

00:01:25.059 --> 00:01:32.059
apps, R Markdown, dashboards, Plumber APIs, and quickly source them to other departments.

00:01:32.059 --> 00:01:38.040
And Package Manager would allow us to centralize and manage how our team uses internal and

00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:39.860
external packages.

00:01:39.860 --> 00:01:44.419
So needless to say, this was an incredible win for my team, and we were super excited

00:01:44.419 --> 00:01:46.220
to get started.

00:01:46.220 --> 00:01:50.779
But because of how quickly everything was moving, while I was given the support of a

00:01:50.779 --> 00:01:56.620
fantastic engineer, the bulk of setting up and configuring RStudio Team would fall on

00:01:56.620 --> 00:01:57.620
me.

00:01:57.620 --> 00:02:04.900
Now, I'm very comfortable coding in an R IDE or working with R Markdown documents, but

00:02:04.900 --> 00:02:09.860
I didn't know anything about servers or setting up an infrastructure in the cloud, but I was

00:02:09.860 --> 00:02:13.580
pretty sure that you couldn't code up a server in an R Markdown document.

00:02:13.580 --> 00:02:15.580
So what did I do?

00:02:15.940 --> 00:02:18.740
Well, of course, first I went to Google.

00:02:18.740 --> 00:02:23.740
Now, RStudio has a ton of great guides for administering their products, but since these

00:02:23.740 --> 00:02:29.139
are geared for engineering or sysadmins, I didn't even know where to put all the code

00:02:29.139 --> 00:02:31.380
the guides were talking about.

00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:35.960
And so this was the beginning of my journey into the world of data engineering.

00:02:35.960 --> 00:02:42.899
As I started learning, I realized that there was a huge disconnect between resources available

00:02:42.899 --> 00:02:47.100
for engineers and resources for data scientists to learn engineering tasks.

00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:53.020
I also learned that data scientists, especially in smaller organizations or startups where

00:02:53.020 --> 00:02:58.940
engineering support can be scarce, desperately need access to engineering skills and resources

00:02:58.940 --> 00:03:03.860
if they want to learn to quickly deploy their own data products.

00:03:03.860 --> 00:03:09.179
So today what I want to do is I want to share with you my own roadmap for how to start the

00:03:09.179 --> 00:03:11.899
process of learning data engineering.

00:03:11.899 --> 00:03:16.460
So if you're looking to set up RStudio team, then this talk should be very helpful for

00:03:16.460 --> 00:03:17.460
you.

00:03:17.460 --> 00:03:22.820
But even if your first engineering product includes a different server setup, then most

00:03:22.820 --> 00:03:26.419
of this talk should also apply to you as well.

00:03:26.419 --> 00:03:29.660
So my roadmap is framed around three different parts.

00:03:29.660 --> 00:03:34.820
People, so how you can use people around you and in your organization to help you set up

00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:36.860
your first engineering project.

00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:41.699
Learning, so the most important things for you to learn as a data scientist as you go

00:03:41.699 --> 00:03:47.779
on your data engineering journey, and implementation, what to do when you're actually in the thick

00:03:47.779 --> 00:03:51.100
of things, in the weeds of your project.

00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:57.580
Okay, so you're about to start your first data engineering project.

00:03:57.580 --> 00:03:59.460
What now?

00:03:59.460 --> 00:04:04.619
So even if you're going at this alone or as part of a small group, it's super helpful

00:04:04.619 --> 00:04:07.179
to have an engineer in your corner.

00:04:07.179 --> 00:04:11.460
It's important to understand that your relationship shouldn't be combative.

00:04:12.220 --> 00:04:19.420
I think as a data scientist, very often you want all the data possible at your fingertips,

00:04:19.420 --> 00:04:25.579
whereas engineers, a lot of times they have particular security concerns and don't give

00:04:25.579 --> 00:04:29.200
you the data that you need as quickly as you may want it.

00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:33.619
So it's important to start a good relationship with your engineer and to learn from them

00:04:33.619 --> 00:04:40.100
what their security concerns may be for your server and to understand where their concerns

00:04:40.100 --> 00:04:41.619
are coming from.

00:04:41.619 --> 00:04:46.859
It's also important before you start your project to really understand the value of

00:04:46.859 --> 00:04:47.859
your project.

00:04:47.859 --> 00:04:49.079
Why are you doing this?

00:04:49.079 --> 00:04:50.140
Who will benefit?

00:04:50.140 --> 00:04:53.480
Who will use this new server, this new product?

00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:56.899
Are there people in your organization that you need to train or that you need to bring

00:04:56.899 --> 00:04:59.459
on into your side?

00:04:59.459 --> 00:05:03.459
It's important to make sure that there's kind of a pot of gold at the end of your rainbow,

00:05:03.459 --> 00:05:09.899
because what you're going to be doing is taking time away from your regular data science tasks

00:05:09.899 --> 00:05:13.540
and focusing on a new skill set on data engineering.

00:05:13.540 --> 00:05:19.540
So it's important that before you start, the work that you're doing is going to very clearly

00:05:19.540 --> 00:05:23.739
bring value to you and to your team.

00:05:23.739 --> 00:05:29.959
So technology and learning, specifically for engineering projects, my biggest weakness

00:05:29.959 --> 00:05:34.220
when I started in the beginning was that I wasn't comfortable using Bash.

00:05:34.220 --> 00:05:40.459
For me, it was this kind of scary, black, blinking command line, and I found a lot of

00:05:40.459 --> 00:05:42.140
it very unintuitive.

00:05:42.140 --> 00:05:48.059
There was one-letter commands and arguments that were unintuitive as compared to R.

00:05:48.059 --> 00:05:53.459
So here we have on the left-hand side some R code, and you can see it reads very easily,

00:05:53.459 --> 00:05:54.459
almost like a sentence.

00:05:54.459 --> 00:05:58.619
You can see what's being grouped, what's being counted, whereas the Bash on the right-hand

00:05:58.619 --> 00:06:00.940
side can be kind of confusing.

00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:02.619
There's one-letter commands.

00:06:02.619 --> 00:06:04.420
It's unclear what's happening.

00:06:04.420 --> 00:06:06.700
So it's important to start learning a little bit about this.

00:06:06.700 --> 00:06:09.420
You don't have to learn everything, but start.

00:06:09.420 --> 00:06:12.540
Learn how to move around in your directories.

00:06:12.540 --> 00:06:14.839
Learn how to copy and paste files.

00:06:14.839 --> 00:06:19.500
Learn how to log into your server using something called SSH protocols.

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:23.700
And make sure that you actually have access to the correct files, and if you don't, learn

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:30.540
how to change the access for your files using Bash.

00:06:30.540 --> 00:06:37.100
Another piece of learning that's important, it's important to draw out your actual server

00:06:37.100 --> 00:06:38.100
architecture.

00:06:38.100 --> 00:06:44.260
And when I say draw it out, I mean actually take out a piece of paper and draw it out.

00:06:44.260 --> 00:06:49.579
It can even help to look at AWS architecture diagrams on the internet and try to decipher

00:06:49.579 --> 00:06:51.260
what they mean.

00:06:51.260 --> 00:06:56.420
AWS has a million and a half services, and as a data scientist entering that world, a

00:06:56.420 --> 00:06:59.420
lot of it can be super daunting to understand.

00:06:59.420 --> 00:07:03.820
And so understanding what all the various terms to all the different softwares and products

00:07:03.820 --> 00:07:05.459
can be really helpful.

00:07:05.459 --> 00:07:11.019
And that's why drawing out your diagram, even if it's super simple, can be helpful in organizing

00:07:11.019 --> 00:07:13.380
your work before you start.

00:07:13.380 --> 00:07:18.859
Also sharing that diagram with your engineer can also help you prevent making errors in

00:07:18.859 --> 00:07:23.140
your system before you even start.

00:07:23.140 --> 00:07:28.440
So here's an example of a simplified AWS architecture diagram.

00:07:28.459 --> 00:07:33.320
When you first are drawing it out, it's important to think about which parts can actually talk

00:07:33.320 --> 00:07:39.760
to each other, what is public, what is private, and which parts of the server point to what

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:41.940
other parts of the server.

00:07:41.940 --> 00:07:45.839
So here we have the VPC or the Virtual Private Cloud.

00:07:45.839 --> 00:07:51.799
This is your virtual server and it's hosted on AWS, but you can also host servers on Azure

00:07:51.799 --> 00:07:55.839
or Aptable or other managed services.

00:07:55.839 --> 00:08:00.320
Here is where we have the meat of what makes RStudio Team, RStudio Team.

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:08.200
We have three EC2 instances or three smaller servers that have all the data that make up

00:08:08.200 --> 00:08:11.359
RStudio Server Pro, Connect, and Package Manager.

00:08:11.359 --> 00:08:16.880
So these EC2 instances live in a private subnet, which create a layer of added security so

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:21.220
that random people can just access your server.

00:08:21.220 --> 00:08:24.459
So here we have a bunch of extra layers of security.

00:08:24.459 --> 00:08:29.040
We have a load balancer, which helps route the correct requests to your servers.

00:08:29.040 --> 00:08:33.979
We also have a bastion or jump box, which adds yet another security layer so that you

00:08:33.979 --> 00:08:36.619
don't jump directly into the RStudio Server.

00:08:36.619 --> 00:08:41.020
You have to go through an added jump box in order to get into your server.

00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:46.539
Now once again, this is a simplified model, but it starts to show you what AWS products

00:08:46.539 --> 00:08:53.140
you as the data engineer have to start setting up in the cloud.

00:08:53.140 --> 00:08:58.859
Now one last piece is another important learning topic that's critical before you start your

00:08:58.859 --> 00:09:03.460
project, and this is learning a little bit about ports and security.

00:09:03.460 --> 00:09:09.280
So this is a huge topic, but it's helpful to know just a little bit about how computers

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:14.979
network and a little bit about security management and the most common internet protocols that

00:09:14.979 --> 00:09:16.500
are used.

00:09:16.500 --> 00:09:21.500
This is one of those topics that engineers seem to know a lot about, but when I was learning,

00:09:21.500 --> 00:09:26.340
I found there weren't that many resources available specifically for data scientists.

00:09:26.340 --> 00:09:32.500
So ports are communication endpoints that allow computers to talk to each other in various

00:09:32.500 --> 00:09:33.500
secure ways.

00:09:33.500 --> 00:09:38.700
We have port 22, 25, 80, 443.

00:09:38.700 --> 00:09:44.179
These are things like HTTP, HTTPS, things that you may have heard about, but it's important

00:09:44.179 --> 00:09:48.059
to learn just a little bit about what ports are available, which ones you have to turn

00:09:48.059 --> 00:09:50.260
on and off in your server.

00:09:51.020 --> 00:09:58.059
SSL and TLS protocols are protocols that make secure internet communication possible by

00:09:58.059 --> 00:10:00.380
encrypting internet traffic.

00:10:00.380 --> 00:10:05.340
I like to think of this as a handshake between different computers.

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:09.539
Setting up these protocols requires learning a little bit about different certificates

00:10:09.539 --> 00:10:14.940
and configurations, so it's important to learn what protocol you're going to be using when

00:10:14.940 --> 00:10:17.260
setting up your project.

00:10:17.859 --> 00:10:23.059
Okay, so you've done your learning and now it's time for implementation.

00:10:23.059 --> 00:10:26.099
My main piece of advice is to get started.

00:10:26.099 --> 00:10:31.299
Obviously, do your research, but don't fall into the trap of analysis paralysis.

00:10:31.299 --> 00:10:34.979
I think for me as a data scientist, I kind of want to know everything available before

00:10:34.979 --> 00:10:39.859
I started, but what happened is that I did two weeks of research and then realized I

00:10:39.859 --> 00:10:43.940
had nothing to show for it other than theoretical knowledge.

00:10:44.659 --> 00:10:51.780
It's helpful here to take a lesson from your engineering teams and use a more agile approach

00:10:51.780 --> 00:10:56.219
where you get started quickly, you may fail quickly, but then you can get started again

00:10:56.219 --> 00:10:57.219
just as quickly.

00:10:57.219 --> 00:11:03.859
All right, so you've officially started your project, what do you do now?

00:11:03.859 --> 00:11:08.059
Use your engineer as a guide and to check in on your work.

00:11:08.059 --> 00:11:13.059
They can tell you when you've done something horribly wrong, like when I accidentally opened

00:11:13.059 --> 00:11:17.820
all of my instances to the entire world, and they can also help you to finish tasks

00:11:17.820 --> 00:11:21.700
that you may not have the appropriate security clearances for.

00:11:21.700 --> 00:11:26.739
So for example, if you want to point your server at a particular domain name, they can

00:11:26.739 --> 00:11:31.619
help you to do that and they could also help you to estimate costs for your server.

00:11:31.619 --> 00:11:37.419
Learning, so it's important to start looking at the new data formats and files that you're

00:11:37.419 --> 00:11:39.500
going to be using in your server.

00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:45.020
So to set up RStudio Teams specifically, RStudio uses something called the Cloud Formation

00:11:45.020 --> 00:11:48.099
Template to set up push button deployment.

00:11:48.099 --> 00:11:51.619
Now when I started looking at this, I was very excited because it looked like something

00:11:51.619 --> 00:11:56.940
very similar to something in the R world, and that is that it looked basically like

00:11:56.940 --> 00:11:58.700
a YAML file.

00:11:58.700 --> 00:12:03.219
So it's important to get to know these files, don't just deploy them, look at them, read

00:12:03.219 --> 00:12:05.500
through them, understand their defaults.

00:12:05.500 --> 00:12:09.739
So when I started, I did not look at the defaults of my Cloud Formation file, and then

00:12:09.739 --> 00:12:14.880
I had to destroy my entire stack and start from scratch because I didn't change a really

00:12:14.880 --> 00:12:16.119
important default.

00:12:16.119 --> 00:12:20.659
So get to know your files, get to know your file formats, read through them, understand

00:12:20.659 --> 00:12:23.020
their defaults.

00:12:23.020 --> 00:12:26.859
So implementation, you are going to be making mistakes.

00:12:26.859 --> 00:12:33.580
So make sure that you set up guardrails and fail-safes for those potential mistakes.

00:12:33.659 --> 00:12:36.739
First, take screenshots of your instances.

00:12:36.739 --> 00:12:39.340
This is something that you can do in AWS.

00:12:39.340 --> 00:12:43.219
When you set up your server, after you configure your server, you're actually able to take

00:12:43.219 --> 00:12:44.880
a screenshot of it.

00:12:44.880 --> 00:12:48.700
So if you ever mess anything up and you need to go back, you don't have to start over from

00:12:48.700 --> 00:12:49.700
scratch.

00:12:49.700 --> 00:12:55.580
As you're going to be setting up your server, there's going to be lots of passwords, PEM

00:12:55.580 --> 00:13:01.460
keys, .pk keys, certificates, save all of these in a secure way.

00:13:01.460 --> 00:13:04.340
For example, saving them in something like one pass.

00:13:04.340 --> 00:13:07.659
Don't just save them on your local computer.

00:13:07.659 --> 00:13:11.640
And lastly, write good documentation.

00:13:11.640 --> 00:13:15.619
Write good documentation that an engineer can follow, that another data scientist can

00:13:15.619 --> 00:13:19.419
follow, because at the moment, while you're the admin, you may not always be the admin

00:13:19.419 --> 00:13:20.679
for this project.

00:13:20.679 --> 00:13:24.059
So it's important to write good documentation as you go along.

00:13:24.059 --> 00:13:25.659
All right.

00:13:25.659 --> 00:13:31.020
So your server is set up, whether it's for our studio team or for another project.

00:13:31.020 --> 00:13:38.260
Now it's time for the fun part, which is to configure all of your settings and defaults.

00:13:38.260 --> 00:13:44.099
So when you're configuring and after you've set up the main parts of your server, you

00:13:44.099 --> 00:13:47.539
need to get buy-in from the data scientists on your team, because they're going to be

00:13:47.539 --> 00:13:50.419
the ones who are going to be testing your deployment.

00:13:50.419 --> 00:13:55.940
So it was helpful for me, at least, to have a testing log to write down what deployments

00:13:55.940 --> 00:13:58.059
are working, which ones are failing.

00:13:58.059 --> 00:14:03.859
And this is helpful for later, when I was actually writing my documentation.

00:14:03.859 --> 00:14:08.179
Understand who's going to need to be trained in the company alongside your data scientists.

00:14:08.179 --> 00:14:11.659
Don't bring everyone in until you've figured out most of the bugs.

00:14:11.659 --> 00:14:15.260
You don't want to be doing demos for your product when there's still bugs in it.

00:14:15.260 --> 00:14:21.179
So take time to set up training and set up testing way before you're going to be introducing

00:14:21.179 --> 00:14:24.099
it to folks at your company.

00:14:24.099 --> 00:14:29.460
You don't want to discourage your users and the consumers of your product before they

00:14:29.460 --> 00:14:33.539
can get started and get really excited for your new project.

00:14:33.539 --> 00:14:37.659
Set up time for training and make sure that there's a little bit of time before you actually

00:14:37.659 --> 00:14:38.659
start demoing.

00:14:38.659 --> 00:14:47.020
All right, so once you've set up your server, you're now officially the root user with pseudo-access.

00:14:47.020 --> 00:14:51.599
It's important that you use this power for good and not for evil.

00:14:51.599 --> 00:14:57.359
So learn about different types of authorizations, about Google Auth, multi-factor authentication,

00:14:57.359 --> 00:15:00.840
API keys, basic authorization.

00:15:00.840 --> 00:15:04.239
As you're going to be configuring your product, you're going to need to be giving folks in

00:15:04.239 --> 00:15:06.200
your company access to it.

00:15:06.200 --> 00:15:08.039
And this has to be done in a secure manner.

00:15:08.039 --> 00:15:10.200
Your engineer can definitely help you here.

00:15:10.200 --> 00:15:14.919
But knowing a little bit about the differences for different authorization protocols can

00:15:14.919 --> 00:15:16.640
be super duper helpful.

00:15:16.640 --> 00:15:22.200
And once again, you may be the root user now, but you may not be the root user later.

00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:24.200
Implementation.

00:15:24.200 --> 00:15:26.559
This is the fun part for me especially.

00:15:26.559 --> 00:15:29.559
Get inside your server and play around.

00:15:29.559 --> 00:15:31.679
Look at the important main files.

00:15:31.679 --> 00:15:37.000
So for RStudio Server Pro, Studio Connect, and Arc Package Manager, I found that these

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:43.840
five files were super duper important in making sure that deployment was actually working.

00:15:43.840 --> 00:15:48.039
So when I first started, I had a lot of deployment errors, and that's because I realized that

00:15:48.039 --> 00:15:52.119
I hadn't changed some of the defaults in these five files.

00:15:52.119 --> 00:15:57.320
So get into your server, understand what the paths are like, understand what the important

00:15:57.320 --> 00:16:02.799
files are, understand what their defaults are, and how they should be changed, and if

00:16:02.799 --> 00:16:05.239
and when they should be changed.

00:16:05.239 --> 00:16:07.140
All right.

00:16:07.140 --> 00:16:12.640
So this is my entire system for setting up a data engineering project as a data scientist.

00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:17.460
So before you start, partner with an engineer and understand their security concerns as

00:16:17.460 --> 00:16:22.359
well as the larger value that your project brings to the entire team.

00:16:22.359 --> 00:16:27.400
Learn a little bit about Bash, about ports and network administration, and draw out your

00:16:27.400 --> 00:16:30.880
AWS infrastructure diagram on a piece of paper.

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:34.919
And when you're ready to implement, get started as soon as you can.

00:16:34.919 --> 00:16:38.140
Throughout your project, use your engineer as a guide.

00:16:38.140 --> 00:16:43.580
Get comfortable with different data formats and set up guardrails in case of failure.

00:16:43.580 --> 00:16:49.380
Once you've set up your project, take the time to train your team, to test your project,

00:16:49.380 --> 00:16:53.400
and test out any other little bugs and issues that may come up.

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:57.099
Learn a little bit about user authorization and root access.

00:16:57.099 --> 00:17:01.380
And then most importantly, get inside your server, play around, and start changing your

00:17:01.380 --> 00:17:03.640
defaults to your needs.

00:17:03.640 --> 00:17:06.979
And finally, remember to have fun.

00:17:06.979 --> 00:17:10.339
Thank you so much for taking the time to listen to this talk.

00:17:10.339 --> 00:17:14.780
I look forward to answering your questions and connecting over the rest of this conference.

